National Trust spys on the secret life of bats
A new research being carried out on a farm in the Highlands of Scotland aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland association will follow bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as bats Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auratus in the Inverewe gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key locations around the property to keep track of bats activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with manual detectors.
An audio analysis conducted by experts of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat calls and what each species is doing.
Next, a habitat map will be developed to create a detailed picture of the landscape scale of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, expects the results to show which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they use each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and what is the best way to keep forests for bats and other associated species.
Morcego populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have decreased considerably in the last century.
These animals overcome threatened by construction and development works that affect children and loss of habitat.
Aerogenerators and lighting also pose a risk, as well as trappings with glue for flies, some chemical treatments of building materials and domestic cat attacks.
The bats aren't blind,
but because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when hunting.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight trajectory.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for over 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the country, is taken very seriously by bats.
It has ten trained experts, who conduct periodic surveys, inspections of children and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organization has even the only and first Scottish bat stock in Three Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the Estate Manager, states that this is the ideal territory for them.
\"In Thrave we have a large area for bats,\" he states.
We count on old buildings, historical trees and a wonderful habitat.
But there are many things that we still don't know about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to prosper --
It emphasizes the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the properties, as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternity baby can kill up to 400 females and offspring, which could exterminate a whole local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, or molest them, as well as destroy their children.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust organization, encourages people to help:
\"There's still much left to learn about bats and, in the case of many of the species, we don't know how it's going to its populations.\"
