Palu is the capital of the province of Central Celebes, which is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Celebes, with an approximate population of 379,800 people in the year 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a regency that is found along over 300 km of coast northwest of the island of Celebes.
This regency, an administrative region less than one province, counted with an approximate population of 299,200 inhabitants in the year 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the main pillars of the Central Celebes province's economy, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mines are also important in the province, but are mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have been affected by tsunamis several times over the past 100 years according to Indonesia's Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also affected the western part of Donggala in 1996, causing the death of nine people.
Indonesia is found over the Pacific Fire Belt of high seismic activity, so it suffers earthquakes regularly.
These are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis that have suffered over the past few years:
2004: A major earthquake on the western coast of the Province of Aceh of Indonesia, in northern Sumatra, which occurred on December 26, provoked a tsunami that affected 14 countries, causing the death of 226,000 people on the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half, in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes affected the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, in front of the coast of Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake of 6.8 degrees of magnitude struck southern Java, the most populated island of Indonesia, causing a tsunami that devastated the southern coast, causing the death of nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake of 7.6 degrees of magnitude occurred near the city of Padang, the capital of the province of Western Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: An earthquake of 7.5 degrees of magnitude affected the Mentawai Islands, located opposite Sumatra, causing a tsunami of up to 10 meters that destroyed dozens of people and resulted in the death of approximately 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake affected Pidie Jaya's regency, located in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, as people remembered the devastation caused by the deadly earthquake and tsunami of 2004.
