Information on the Red Tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report of the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Conservation Commission is producing a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the aforementioned commission, increasingly unequal flowering conditions are being observed in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which is possible to mean that concentrations are being reduced.
The red tide stretches approximately 210 km from the coast from the counties in the north of Pinellas to those in southern Lee.
Concentrations of 16 km away from Hillsboroug County coast can be found, but in fewer places compared to last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
It was reported the presence of mid-level concentrations on the coast or far from the coast of the county of Pinellas last week, bottom and high concentrations away from the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom and high concentrations on or off the coast of the county of Sarasota, bottom and middle-level concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom and high concentrations on or off the coast with Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier's counties it is reported that cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No such cases were reported in the northwest of Florida during the past week.
